Syntax:

ansible all -m MODULE -a "ARGUMENTS" -i inventory

SYSTEM MODULES
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

All Ansible modules need Python on target:
Exception — raw module (no Python needed):

ping        → Test connectivity
              ansible all -m ping

command     → Run command (no shell, no pipes)
              ansible all -m command -a "uptime"

shell       → Run via /bin/sh (supports pipes)
              ansible all -m shell -a "df -h | grep /dev"

raw         → No Python needed on target
              ansible all -m raw -a "yum install python3 -y"

reboot      → Reboot and wait for host to come back
              ansible all -m reboot

setup       → Gather all facts about host
              ansible all -m setup


FILE MODULES
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

copy        → Copy file to remote host
              ansible all -m copy -a "src=/tmp/a.txt dest=/tmp/a.txt"

fetch       → Pull file FROM remote to local
              ansible all -m fetch -a "src=/var/log/app.log dest=/tmp/"

file        → Create / delete / chmod / chown
              ansible all -m file -a "path=/tmp/test state=directory"

lineinfile  → Add or edit a line inside a file
              ansible all -m lineinfile -a "path=/etc/hosts line='1.1.1.1 app'"

stat        → Check if file exists, get file info
              ansible all -m stat -a "path=/etc/nginx"


PACKAGE / SERVICE MODULES
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

yum         → Install package on RHEL / Amazon Linux
              ansible all -m yum -a "name=nginx state=present"

apt         → Install package on Ubuntu / Debian
              ansible all -m apt -a "name=nginx state=present"

service     → Start / stop / restart a service
              ansible all -m service -a "name=nginx state=started"

user        → Create / delete system users
              ansible all -m user -a "name=deploy state=present"

cron        → Add / remove cron jobs
              ansible all -m cron -a "name=backup minute=0 hour=2 job='/backup.sh'"


COMMAND vs SHELL
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

command  →  no pipes   no redirects   no variables   ✅ safer
shell    →  pipes ✅   redirects ✅   variables ✅   use when needed

# FAILS  → ansible all -m command -a "df -h | grep /dev"
# WORKS  → ansible all -m shell   -a "df -h | grep /dev"


STATE VALUES (used in -a arguments)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

state=present   → install / create
state=absent    → remove / delete
state=started   → start service
state=stopped   → stop service
state=restarted → restart service
state=directory → create directory
state=file      → ensure it is a file
state=touch     → touch the file
